dict.string: ES = Early Start for the first activity is typically “0”.  The successor (next) activity uses the EF of the predecessor (previous) activity.

DUR = Duration that was chosen for the activity and is based on the calculation:

DUR = Quantity/Productivity Rate

EF = Early Finish is based on the calculation:

EF = ES + DUR

LS = Late Start is based on the calculation:

LS = LF - DUR

TF = Total Float is based on the calculations: 

TF = LS - ES & 

TF = LF - EF

*Note: Both calculations 

should have same result.
LF = Late Finish uses the LS of the Successor activity. Also, on the last activity of a project (last node), the LF uses the EF of that activity before starting the Backward Pass.
ACTIVITY = Activity is the item of work that needs to be started and finished, within the time allowed and NOT extend project completion time.

Welcome to the Precedence Diagram Method (PDM) Simulation of a network diagram using a Finish to Start activity relationship. Before starting the simulation you may want to take a look at some of the terminology that will be used in the simulation. Please mouse over the boxes at the left to expose an explanation of items such as ES, DUR etc. Once you have covered the basic terms you can start the simulation from the link in the upper right corner.

PDM LAYOUT: 

The first step in creating the diagram is laying out the activities based on the data that was acquired in planning for the project.  The project data in this case already has activities assigned (Act ID & Descriptions), along with the Duration (Dur) and the Predecessor (Pred) or previous activity.  As you can see, the start of the project Early Start (ES) is listed at “0” as a typical scenario. The other ES and Early Finish (EF) dates will follow. This first step you will notice that the ES & EF dates will be moving from left to right in which is called the Forward Pass which is covered in the next section.


For this section on a PDM Layout use your mouse and move over items in the columns to the left to see the relationship, with the diagram below and the data. Then click on the "NEXT: Forward Pass" Link to move to the next section.

FORWARD PASS: 

In this section we will analyze how the calculations on the diagram at the bottom of the screen were achieved. Please review the node at the left for the ES and EF dates and what happens if there is more than one Predecessor to an activity.

The Early Date values have been solved so you can mouse over each of the ES and EF boxes in the nodes on the diagram below, which will return an explanation of the values. Then click on the "NEXT: Backward Pass" Link to move to the next section.

FLOAT: 

In this section we will analyze how the calculations on the diagram at the bottom of the screen were achieved. Please review the node at the left for TF.

The Total Float values have been solved so you can mouse over the TF boxe in the nodes on the diagram below, which will return an explanation of the values. Then click on the "NEXT: Critical Path" Link to move to the next section.

CRITICAL PATH: 

After the Total Float values are calculated, you can analyze the schedule to determine the Critical Path. Activities with a “0” TF value identify items on the Critical Path (more than one path is possible). Critical items on a schedule are important because, they have to be done on time or the project will be delayed.


Mouse over the Critical Path button at the left to reveal the Critical Path.
